The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Brad Hogg charged 
                                                Brad Hogg charged 
            A STAFF REPORTER                       
	Calcutta: Australian spinner Brad Hogg was on Tuesday charged under Level 3 of the International Cricket Councils Code of Conduct following allegations that he abused Anil Kumble and Mahendra Singh Dhoni.         
	[That Hogg will be charged for using abusive language was reported by The Telegraph on Monday.]         
	Hogg has been accused of making an offensive remark during Indias second innings of the Sydney Test.         
	Under the terms of the Code of Conduct, Match Referee Mike Procter will hold a hearing as soon as reasonably practicable. The preliminary date for the hearing is set for January 14 in Perth.         
	The alleged offence has been reported under clause 3.3 of the Code of Conduct which refers to players or team officials using language or gestures that offends, insults, humiliates, intimidates, threatens, disparages or vilifies another person on the basis of that persons race, religion, gender, colour, descent, or national or ethic origin.         
	The penalty for a Level 3 offence is a ban of between two and four Tests or between four and eight ODIs. Harbhajan Singh was also reported under the same clause and later found guilty of racially abusing Andrew Symonds.                                                                                                                        
